## Coding Rules — ALWAYS FOLLOW THESE

1. TypeScript only — no .jsx or .js files
2. Tailwind v4 only — no tailwind.config.js, no inline styles
3. Mobile-first — design for 390px first, scale up
4. Thumb-friendly — 44px min tap targets, no hover-only interactions
5. UK standards — £, miles, UK postcodes, DD/MM/YYYY, British English
6. No passwords ever — Magic Link auth only
7. Supabase client — always import from src/lib/supabase.ts
8. Icons — lucide-react only
9. Friction is the enemy — max 5 fields recruiters, max 3 fields candidates
10. RLS always — every query scoped to correct user. Recruiter/employer queries must filter by employer_id or recruiter_id; see supabase/QUERY_SCOPE_AUDIT.md.
11. GDPR — consent language wherever data is collected
12. Self-declared — RTW, NI, DBS always labelled clearly
13. No CV required — entry-level roles apply without CV
14. Skeleton loaders — all async fetches show skeletons, never blank
15. Optimistic UI — status updates apply locally first, rollback on error
16. Sheet not navigate — candidate review opens in Shadcn Sheet
17. Never show full postcode — outward code only in UI
18. No nested ternaries in JSX — extract into named functions above component
19. No IIFEs in JSX — extract into named render functions instead
20. tabular-nums on ALL numeric data
21. Truth Engine colours are semantic — never decorative
22. Postcode API calls — strip spaces: postcode.replace(/\s+/g, '')
23. Design tokens — always use v2.0 tokens, never old (#0f1624 / #141f33 / #2a3a5c / #6b7fa3)
24. Font — DM Sans for UI, DM Mono for numeric data

---

## UX Principles
- Scannability over aesthetics — Pay, Location, Shift must be
  highest contrast elements on job cards
- Speed first — >5 fields for recruiters or >3 for candidates
  means something is wrong
- No ghosting — every action has a visible outcome
- Truth Engine — show commute, skills match, RTW on job cards
  when candidate is logged in, before they apply
- Apply button always fully visible — never fade on hover
- Bottom sheet for apply flow — never a centred modal on mobile

